node.text:
The MICHELIN Guide makes you discover the diversity of Zagreb's culinary scene and its rich cuisine built around exceptional local products. We stop at @res_tac_ where we meet chef @miletic_v, her gardener and her producers coming from Zagreb County. The men show us their wonderful range of local products (goat cheese, wine and honey) and share their specific attributes with us.
 
On the threshold between East and West, Zagreb and its county offer a rich and stunning gastronomic scene embodied by talented chefs who are devoted to highlighting the quality of the local ingredients. In a residential district outside the city centre, chef Vesna Miletic prepares Mediterranean-influenced dishes composed of fresh product directly coming from the city markets and her local producers. Let's discover a female chef, her producers and their product which make the gastronomic reputation of this stunning capital city!
 
Cosmopolitan buzz of @zagrebtourist and @visitzagrebcounty may strike you.
 
📍 Zagreb, Croatia . .

The MICHELIN Guide takes you to Zagreb to discover the treasures of the capital city of Croatia, their chefs, their products and their producers. We take a closer look at the establishment @esplanadezagreb where Chef @anagrgicchef runs the kitchen of two restaurants Zinfandel's and Le Bistro Esplanade – both distinguished with a Plate in the MICHELIN Guide Croatia 2020.
 
On the threshold between East and West, Zagreb and its county offer a rich and stunning gastronomic scene marrying culinary influences from continental and Mediterranean countries. Among the restaurants of the city, two are housed in Esplanade hotel considered as one of the capital's most popular places for eating. While the French classic Bistro is a smartly dressed yet informal all-day place, the luxurious Zinfandel's restaurant effortlessly combines the elegance of a bygone era with the ambience of a contemporary dining room. Chef Ana Grgić Tomić prepares ambitious menus offering Croatian classics, like strukli, alongside modern European dishes.
 
Cosmopolitan buzz of @zagrebtourist and @visitzagrebcounty may strike you.
 
📍 Zagreb, Croatia

To celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day, chefs and heads  of restaurants awarded a MICHELIN Green Star are sharing some recipes with us that help make the world a little greener!
 
Today, it’s Chef @dominiquecrenn’s turn. At the head of three-MICHELIN-Starred @atelier.crenn in San Francisco, she chips in with this offering that is a  great way to eat up all those perfect summer tomatoes. Today’s recipe is for juicy, simple confit and marinated tomato salad – one of her favorite ways to enjoy this simple pleasure!
 
Yield: 4

Thanks for the recipe, Chef Dominique Crenn! 

Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguideand use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

node.title: MICHELIN Guide At Home - Dominique Crenn’s Tomato Salad

node.text:
To celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day, chefs at the head of restaurants awarded a MICHELIN Green Star are sharing some recipes that help make the world a little greener!
 
To @massimobottura, it’s essential to “never let food go to waste.” The Chef of Three-MICHELIN-Starred Osteria Francescana shares this message of hope and goodwill in the form of his grandmother’s recipe for traditional Passatelli. In this recipe, the star of the show are humble breadcrumbs, which are for him the epitome of the “waste not, want not” food ethic.
 
Thanks for the recipe, Chef Massimo Bottura! 

Illustrations by @alice.vdw 
Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguide and use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

node.title: MICHELIN Guide At Home - Massimo Bottura’s Passatelli

Today we celebrate International Sustainable Gastronomy Day with chefs and foodies around the world. 

We’re kicking it off with this amazing recipe for herb butter artichoke tacos handed to us from Chef Gary Yin, who helms restaurant King’s Joy in Beijing, 3 stars and a MICHELIN Green star in the MICHELIN China Guide 2021. 
 
Celebrate with us by making the recipe at home and share the results in your story tagging @MICHELINGUIDE and @legengaryin!
 
Serves: 4, 3 tacos per pax

Tip from the chef: You can crack fresh black pepper and/or a few drops of Tabasco for more pop!

Thanks for the recipe, Chef Gary Yin! 

Share your version with us 👉Tag @michelinguide and use #MICHELINGUIDEATHOME

Congratulations to @tsukiminyc on its MICHELIN Star! Chef-partner Takanori Ayikama chatted with @ericripert of Three Star Le Bernardin about hospitality and kaiseki with seasonal ingredients. 

Our Inspectors say, "The name Tsukimi references the mid-autumn harvest festival honoring the moon at its fullest and brightest. With that seasonal approach in mind, Chef Takanori Akiyama has created a deeply personal interpretation of a proper kaiseki meal. 

Thanks to our partner @wineaccess! #wineaccess

See the entire MICHELIN Guide New York selection for 2021 at https://bit.ly/3tL6PYT
and stay tuned for more of the 2021 MICHELIN Guide announcements.

node.text:
How do chefs around the world prepare the ultimate edible flower? 

If you are among those who know the pleasure of ripping through steamed leaves to the meaty heart at the fuzzy center (or you have never tried to do such a thing), you may be surprised to realize that artichokes work in plenty of recipes. With its layers of leaves and flavorsome heart, this vegetable is actually a variety of a species of edible thistle. The edible portion of the plant is composed of the flower buds before the flowers come into bloom.
Boiled, grilled, braised, or stuffed and baked, artichokes are a unique ingredient worth incorporating into cooking, even into the most famous chefs' cuisine.
 
This month, our culinary world tour continues by spotlighting this delicious ingredient sublimated by chefs based around the world. Here’s how! 🍴  1. Artichoke and rosemary by chef @nikoromito from @ristorantereale 📷 Brambilla Serrani
2. Artichoke soup with black truffle, black truffle strips and Parmesan shavings by chef @guysavoy 📷 Laurence Mouton
3. Turbot, artichokes, olive sauce by chef @luke.tipping from @simpsons_restaurant  
4. Artichoke with truffle marrow by chef Pier Paolo Picchi from @restaurantepicchi 📷 @cru.do and @jrbronko
 
📷 Sakura Ho  #BasicsAroundTheWorld #cuisine #ingredient #artichoke #foodlover #MICHELINrestaurants #MICHELINstars

Today’s recipe is for small French cakes with a rectangular shape: Financier. Traditionally made from ground almonds, this spongy delicacy with a crispy outside may make a great snack. Our pastry chef of the day decided to substitute the traditional powder with hazelnut powder to boost the nutty aroma even more.
This recipe is a gift from Eric Raynal, pastry chef at Le Jardin de Berne – One Star in the MICHELIN Guide France 2021 – attached to @chateaudeberne.
 
Measurement equivalents:
160g= 5.6 oz
60g= 2.1 oz
2g= 1 teaspoon
90g= 3.2 oz
15g= 0.5 oz
 Tip of the chef: If you want to keep the cake and taste it later, you can freeze the baked cake and then thaw it in the oven for 8 minutes.
 
Thanks for the recipe, Chef @eric_raynal!

Illustrations by @alice.vdw

Five restaurants have joined the One MICHELIN Star list in the 2021 selection for Taipei. Congratulations!
 
Named “By Night” in French, @denuit_taipei's decor is aptly furnished according to its name, respecting the French traditions and the seasonality of ingredients.
@fujintreechampagne pairs re-imagined Taiwanese favorites with French bubbly.
T+T, whose name is an abbreviation of “Tapas Tasting” provides a creative take on Spanish tapas.
The Taiwanese restaurant Mipon @grandmayfull specializes in refined home-style Taiwanese cooking that boasts intricate details and modern twists.
At @mudantempura in the Da’an District, seasonal ingredients from Taiwan and Japan are coated in a delicate batter, deep-fried to perfection. 

📍  Taipei

node.text:
The highlight of the MICHELIN Guide Taipei & Taichung 2021 is that two restaurants have been awarded 1 Star with our highest honor, bringing the total number of 1-Star restaurants in Taichung to four.
 
@oretachinonikuya – meaning “our meat house” in Japanese – received a first MICHELIN Star. The yakiniku restaurant offers prized Hida beef cuts and rare breeds, with only the most premium cuts making it to the grill — along with a secret menu for those in the know.
Promoted to 1 Star, the restaurant @sur_cuisine reflects on the young chef-owner’s vision to elevate everyday Taiwanese ingredients to haute cuisine through the use of modern techniques and a prix fixe menu that changes every season. 

📍  Taichung

Among the new MICHELIN Guide Taipei & Taichung 2021 selection, L'Atelier de Joël Robuchon, is the unique restaurant to be promoted to Two MICHELIN Stars this year.

node.text:
The plate of the day is a soup from the 3-Star #nihonryoriryugin that combines the finest ingredients, all carefully selected in Japan. Served in a bowl of Yamanaka lacquerware, the ‘Fujin Raijin Bowl’ is composed of a Dashi made by cooking a soft-shell turtle with spring water from Fuji, ginjo Sake and two types of kombucha seasoned with algae salt, ultra-thin salty soy sauce, and red sake. A traditional craftsman from Wajima painted the black bowl based on the chef’s design. 
 
🍴 Dashi soup with soft-shell turtle, grilled rice cake, egg tofu and green onion.

📍 Tokyo, Japan

#MICHELINrestaurants #restaurants #gastronomy #dashi #japanasefood #foodies #foodiegram #instafood #ThreeMICHELINStars #MICHELINGuideTOKYO

Today’s recipe is from Asimakis Chaniotis, Executive Chef of @piedaterrerestaurant in Fitzrovia – 1 Star in the MICHELIN Guide Great Britain and Ireland. His cold shellfish gazpacho soup is perfect for the warm summer weather. 

Asimakis was brought up on the Greek island of Kefalonia and spent many years fishing the surrounding seas with family and friends. His dishes feature the stunning ingredients he caught and he now uses his childhood as inspiration for his dishes here in London.

Measurement equivalents:
50ml= 1.8 fl.oz
100ml=3.5 fl.oz
1kg= 35.3 oz
2L=70.4 fl.oz
Servings: 2

Tip of the chef: To intensify the flavour of the dish, you can add 1g of saffron to the shellfish soup and top with sea urchin and herbs before serving.

Thank you for the recipe @asimakis!

Illustrations by @alice.vdw
